# Day 3 - AWS Auto Scaling

## Objective

Learn how to configure Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling to automatically launch new EC2 instances when CPU utilization increases and distribute traffic using an Application Load Balancer (ALB).

---

## Services Used

- Amazon EC2
- Amazon Machine Image (AMI)
- Launch Template
- Auto Scaling Group (ASG)
- Application Load Balancer (ALB)
- Target Group
- Amazon CloudWatch
- Amazon Linux 2023
- Apache HTTP Server (httpd)

---

## Architecture

Client

↓

Application Load Balancer

↓

Target Group

↓

Auto Scaling Group

↓

EC2 Instances

---

## Practical Steps

### Step 1

Created an Amazon Linux 2023 EC2 instance.

Installed Apache HTTP Server.

sudo yum install httpd -y
sudo systemctl enable --now httpd
echo “Hello Apache” > /var/www/html/index.html
---

### Step 2

Created a custom Amazon Machine Image (AMI) from the configured web server.

---

### Step 3

Created a Launch Template using the custom AMI.

---

### Step 4

Created an Auto Scaling Group.

Configuration:

- Desired Capacity: 1
- Minimum Capacity: 1
- Maximum Capacity: 4

---

### Step 5

Created an Application Load Balancer.

Configured:

- Internet Facing
- HTTP Listener (Port 80)

---

### Step 6

Created a Target Group.

Configuration:

- Target Type: Instance
- Protocol: HTTP
- Port: 80

---

### Step 7

Attached the Auto Scaling Group to the Target Group.

Verified that the EC2 instance became Healthy.

---

### Step 8

Installed the **stress** package.

sudo yum install stress -y

Generated CPU load.

stress --cpu 2 --timeout 300

---

### Step 9

Observed that Auto Scaling automatically launched a new EC2 instance when CPU utilization exceeded the configured threshold.

---

### Step 10

Verified that the newly launched EC2 instance was automatically registered with the Target Group and became Healthy.

---

## Result

Successfully configured Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling with an Application Load Balancer to automatically launch new EC2 instances during high CPU utilization and distribute incoming traffic across healthy instances.
